Did I ever tell y'all the story about getting Winnie?
Many of you know how heartbroken we were when our boy Pele🐾 passed away suddenly last January. 
The decision to get another pup wasn't immediate. It's so hard saying goodbye and it took time to heal and regroup. 
By late spring I couldn't stand it anymore and knew we needed dog energy back in our lives.
I knew for me this dog had to be something pele would approve of too, so it couldn't be a boy, and for us it couldn't be black or a lab... basically it had to be opposite of Pele😉
I decided we needed a female Golden Retriever and I told hubs that's what I want for my Birthday. 
Well, you don't just go get one of those I quickly learned. 
I finally found a breeder in May and got on the waiting list for a female.
No guarantees on when it will happen... you just wait.
Her litter was born in July. I saw her and immediately fell in love. She was the lightest and biggest of the 3 girls. 
But we were last on the list so didn't get to choose. 
I thought "well, she'll be first pick so don't even get your hopes up."
Wrong! She was the one left so was OURS!
and then the breeder told me the pick up day would be August 27th... which happens to be my birthday. 
I know Pele or my Angels or something out there was pulling some strings to make my Bday wish come true.
Thank you Universe, Thank you Pele.

Recently,  I've changed my coffee buying criteria. Specifically, I only want to support farms that don't destroy bird and wildlife habitats.
I've found a couple of brands in the grocery store that have the Rainforest Alliance stamp, but I'll need to order online for bird friendly. 
.
If you're interested in this, too, here's a little more info from @audubonsociety:

If you can afford it, opt for beans that are certified shade-grown, which are stamped with seals such as “Rainforest Alliance Certified” or “Bird Friendly." Both certifications require farmers to maintain or restore some level of canopy cover—a proxy for “forest-like”—and prohibit harmful pesticides, which limit prey for birds. The Bird Friendly certification, developed by the Smithsonian Migratory Bird Center, is considered a slightly more rigorous standard from a conservation perspective (its rules related to canopy cover, pesticide use, and product purity are stricter). But both seals point consumers to coffee that maintains some habitat for birds.

Description:
A fawn stands facing the viewer surrounded by a lush green forest. A bright light burst through the leaves in the upper left corner with rays of light emi ating through the forest. There are translucent,  light filled hummingbirds flying towards the light with one Rufous hummingbird, colorful and detailed, and is facing the viewer with wings outstretched, just above the fawn. There are ferns and other plants and lots of bokeh bubbles across the canvas in pale yellows, white, pinks,  and greens. A large indigo milk cap mushroom is next to the fawn coming out from the forest floor.The fawns spots and light fur captures these colors and reflects them. There are bits of gold in the spots. A fantastical, otherworldly scene.

I haven't played with Naphthol red in so long. 
This is a Naphthol crimson, and of course, being an Enneagram 5, I google everything because I'm curious😆
.
Naphthol Crimson is used in many ways besides its power as a pure red in graphic arts. Mixed with Ultramarine Blue it makes beautiful violets, although softer more muted violets and mauves can be made by varying the blue used such as trying Cobalt Blue or for even softer and more neutral colors try mixing with Cerulean Blue. Mixed with white it gives cool pinks, and mixed with Burnt Umber it gives a warm burgundy color. It truly is a versatile friend for the artist.

I love this technique.  It adds beautiful texture.
Just find a leaf or flower or stems...mix up a color and brush it onto the textured side of the leaf and press it into the canvas.
I can usually get several pressings from one application of paint🎨

I've always been creative, but for the first several  decades of my life, I was mostly a dilettante until I committed to painting.
I remember a conversation with an actress friend I was living with in LA in the late 90s (who is now an academy award winning actress, btw, so this is good advice)
I was pursuing acting and had done a few things by that point. 
She asked me if I absolutely loved acting, was it something I felt like I must do to be happy, did I NEED it?
And in that moment, I realized I didn't feel that way about it or anything I had done up to that point. 
I dipped my toes in the music biz after that.
I loved writing and recording music, I taught myself guitar, I sang (not the greatest), but I made some records and worked with some great people. 
But still,  it wasn't my thing. 
Also, at this point in the story? I'm in my late 30s.
There's more in between, but this is already way too wordy.

when I started painting almost a decade ago, I finally understood what it was like to feel that way about something. 

Yes, I MUST paint. I LOVE painting. 
Do you know why that's important?
Because being an artist is effing HARD.
Your love for it carries you through all the challenging times.
Your need for it keeps you coming back to the studio every morning,  enthusiastic about what will happen on the canvas today.

Maybe this speaks to you today. 
Consider your "why" for whatever it is you're pursuing in your life. 
The rest will follow.
